      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Virtual Tours, 3D Walkthroughs and Video in Brisbane Real Estate Listings
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Each visual format does a different job. Here is what buyers actually use, what it costs, and when a 3D tour or drone shoot earns its place in your marketing budget.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Visual marketing is where a lot of seller money gets spent without a clear view of what is actually earning its place. Agents will quote packages that bundle photos, video, 3D tour, drone, and twilight shots into a single line item, and sellers sign off without knowing which of those formats is driving buyer engagement and which is window dressing.</p>

      <p>The honest answer is that each format does a specific job, and the right mix depends on the property, the target buyer pool, and the campaign budget. This article walks through the five main formats, what each one actually does for a listing, what it costs in Brisbane, and when it is worth the spend.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The five main formats</h2>
      <p><strong>2D photos</strong> are the standard still photography in every listing. A professional photographer produces 20 to 40 images covering external, internal, and detail shots. These are the primary images on realestate.com.au, Domain, and all agent websites. Every listing needs these. This is not optional.</p>

      <p><strong>Video walkthroughs</strong> are short, typically 60 to 90 second, scripted or unscripted tours. The format varies: some are agent-led with the agent walking through and speaking to camera, some are cinematic with no voiceover and music underlay, and some are buyer-perspective tours that simulate walking through the property.</p>

      <p><strong>3D virtual tours</strong> (Matterport-style) are navigable 360-degree walkthroughs that buyers control themselves. The buyer clicks to move from room to room, rotates the view, and can access a doll-house view that shows the entire floor plan at once. These are hosted online and linked from the main listing.</p>

      <p><strong>Drone and aerial video</strong> shows the external property from above, along with immediate neighbourhood context: street, surrounding homes, distance to amenities, aspect. For some properties, drone footage is the single most compelling visual in the campaign. For others, it adds nothing that a ground-level external shot does not already convey.</p>

      <p><strong>Twilight or dusk photography</strong> captures external shots at sunset, when warm interior lights contrast with a deepening sky. These images work as aspirational marketing, particularly for architectural properties, pools, and homes with outdoor entertaining areas. They typically supplement rather than replace the standard daytime exterior shots.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What each format actually does</h2>
      <p><strong>Photos</strong> are still the primary format buyers scan. On the major portals, the first 3 to 5 images determine whether a buyer clicks through to the full listing or scrolls past. If the photos do not work, nothing else in the marketing package matters, because the buyer has already moved on.</p>

      <p><strong>Video walkthroughs</strong> create emotional connection. They show the flow between rooms, which static photos cannot do, and they communicate the atmosphere of a home in a way that a grid of images cannot. Serious shortlisted buyers almost always watch the video before deciding whether to attend an open home. For inner-east family homes and Queenslanders with character detail, video regularly outperforms photos in terms of engagement and inspection conversion.</p>

      <p><strong>3D virtual tours</strong> enable deep investigation by serious buyers. The click-through rate on 3D tours is lower than video, but the time-on-tour for buyers who do engage is much longer. A buyer who spends 8 to 12 minutes in a 3D tour is a high-intent buyer who is mentally walking the property. This is particularly valuable when the buyer pool includes distant or interstate buyers who cannot attend in person, and for tenanted properties where repeat physical inspections are harder to arrange.</p>

      <p><strong>Drone</strong> communicates context and aspect. It is most valuable when those attributes matter to the property's value: elevated blocks with views, properties close to parks or rivers, homes on larger blocks where the land is part of the sell, and neighbourhoods where the streetscape is a feature. For a standard mid-block house on a standard street, drone often shows nothing that changes the buyer's assessment.</p>

      <p><strong>Twilight</strong> is marketing impact, not information. It does not tell the buyer anything about the property they could not learn from the standard exterior shot. What it does is position the listing emotionally, particularly for premium homes where the aspirational feel of the campaign affects how buyers price the property in their own mind.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When a 3D virtual tour pays off</h2>
      <p>The 3D tour is the format sellers ask about most, and it is the one with the most situational value. It is worth the spend in four clear scenarios.</p>

      <p>First, higher-value properties where distant or interstate buyers make up a meaningful part of the buyer pool. A $2m plus Camp Hill or Morningside home frequently attracts Sydney or Melbourne relocators who cannot fly up to inspect every shortlisted property. A 3D tour lets those buyers qualify the property thoroughly before booking travel.</p>

      <p>Second, properties with unique flow or layout that photos cannot fully convey. Queenslanders with multiple levels, split-level renovations, unusual room configurations, or homes where the connection between indoor and outdoor spaces is a key feature all benefit from 3D tours. The tour conveys the spatial relationship in a way that even a good floor plan cannot.</p>

      <p>Third, investment properties where remote buyers want to evaluate without visiting. An investor assessing a property they will rent out is often indifferent to the emotional aspects of the home and wants to understand layout, condition, and dimensions. A 3D tour satisfies that need more efficiently than a stream of physical inspections.</p>

      <p>Fourth, tenanted properties where repeat inspection access is limited. Under Queensland legislation, tenants must consent to inspections and a campaign that maximises each scheduled access window benefits from having a 3D tour that buyers can explore online between open homes. This reduces the pressure on physical inspection slots.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When a 3D virtual tour is not worth it</h2>
      <p>Small apartments where photos and a floor plan convey the full layout do not benefit enough to justify the cost. A 60 square metre one-bedroom apartment with a simple layout is a case where the tour adds little that buyers did not already know from five photos.</p>

      <p>Properties where the appeal is intensely sensory, such as gardens, pools, outlooks, and views, are not well served by 3D tours. The format is strong on spatial layout and weak on atmosphere. For those properties, video and strong photography carry more of the emotional load, and the 3D tour can feel flat.</p>

      <p>Budget-constrained campaigns where the $400 to $800 spend on a 3D tour would be better allocated to stronger photography, a more ambitious video, or expanded portal advertising. The tour is an addition to the core marketing package, not a substitute for it. If the core package is compromised to fund the tour, the campaign has gone the wrong direction.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The cost structure in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>Approximate current pricing for professional property marketing in Brisbane, as a planning reference:</p>

      <p>Professional photography: $400 to $1,000 depending on the number of images and whether dusk shots are included. Video walkthrough: $400 to $1,200 depending on length, editing complexity, and whether an agent voiceover is included. 3D virtual tour (Matterport-style): $400 to $800 for a standard residential property, with hosting fees that typically run for 3 to 12 months before the tour expires. Drone photography: $200 to $500. Twilight external shoot: $300 to $600. Packages that combine photos, video, and drone: $1,200 to $3,000 depending on inclusions.</p>

      <p>These prices vary by provider, by season, and by how the agent packages their supplier relationships. Some agencies bundle marketing into their commission structure; others pass through supplier invoices directly to the seller. Both approaches are legitimate, but the seller should understand which model applies before signing the agency agreement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers actually use</h2>
      <p>On the portals, buyers scan photos first. If the photos do not hold attention, the listing does not get a second look. For listings that pass the photo test, buyers typically watch the video, then scan the floor plan, then explore the 3D tour if one is available. They also read the written description, though usually after the visuals have already formed an impression.</p>

      <p>Distant and interstate buyers rely more heavily on video and 3D tours. They are often deciding whether to book travel to inspect, and the video plus 3D tour package is what makes that decision. A property with strong video and 3D tour will convert more interstate inspections than one without, for the same level of core appeal.</p>

      <p>Decisive buyers still physically inspect before making an offer. Video and 3D tours do not replace inspection; they precede it. The buyer who inspects has typically already seen the video and 3D tour and is coming to confirm what they have already provisionally assessed. If the physical property does not match the online impression, the buyer withdraws quickly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should ask the agent</h2>
      <p>Which formats are included in the quoted marketing package. Ask for an itemised breakdown, not a single package price, so you can see what each component is costing and decide whether it earns its place.</p>

      <p>Which photographer or videographer is being used, and can you see sample work for comparable properties. The quality range across Brisbane providers is wide. The wrong photographer on a good property can cost you more than the whole marketing spend, because the listing underperforms.</p>

      <p>Who owns the resulting media. In most cases, the agent or their contracted supplier owns the photography, video, and 3D tour, and the seller has a licence to use them for the campaign. If the agent is changed mid-campaign or the property is re-listed later, the media may not transfer. Understand this before the campaign, not after.</p>

      <p>How long the 3D tour remains active. Most Matterport scans are hosted for 3 to 12 months under the included package, after which hosting fees apply or the tour is taken offline. For a campaign that runs longer than expected, the 3D tour expiring mid-campaign is an avoidable problem.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What does not work well</h2>
      <p>DIY phone-shot video in place of professional video. It looks amateur, undermines the overall presentation, and signals to buyers that the seller has not invested in the campaign. A listing without a video is better than a listing with a bad video.</p>

      <p>Over-saturating the marketing with every possible format. A listing that opens with a carousel of 40 photos, a 3 minute video, a 3D tour, drone footage, twilight shots, and a virtual staging gallery is exhausting rather than compelling. Buyers disengage from too much content, and the listing fails to leave a clear impression. The best campaigns are focused, not maximal.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>For a typical Brisbane inner-east property in the $1m to $2m range, professional photos and a short, well-produced video walkthrough are the essentials. They carry most of the listing's impact and are the minimum required for a campaign at that price point.</p>

      <p>Add a 3D virtual tour if the property has a unique layout, a significant distant or interstate buyer pool, or is tenanted with restricted inspection access. Add drone if the property's aspect, land, or neighbourhood context is part of the sell. Add twilight for premium homes where the aspirational framing genuinely lifts buyer perception.</p>

      <p>Do not add any of these simply because they are on the agent's standard menu. Each format should earn its place based on what the property needs to communicate and who the target buyer is. A focused, well-produced package beats a bloated one every time.</p>

